{
  "doc_id": "15136",
  "text": "The second gene, ycf68, is located in the trnI-GAU intron. A nearly identical sequence was found in C. sinensis but an additional T insertion near the C-terminus abolished the stop codon at the corresponding position. The intact ycf68 can be detected in several monocots and Nymphaeaceae [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . However, in the majority of other rosids (Figure 3 ) and the rest of the eudicots [CITATION_3] , the ycf68 homologs all contain premature stop codons. Although Raubeson et al. [CITATION_4] argued that ycf68 is not a protein-coding gene based on the lack of intron-folding pattern, the high levels of sequence conservation among the ORFs of identified homologs suggest that the true identity and functionality of this putative gene remains to be further investigated.",
